image.altText: Victoria Cafasso's killer has never been found.

items.synopsis: Italian tourist Victoria Cafasso had been in Tasmania barely a week in 1995 when she was stabbed 17 times on an idyllic beach in broad daylight. Twenty-seven years on, police release new images and reveal they have conducted recent searches.

title.children: Police conducting new searches over grisly unsolved beach murder of Italian tourist Victoria Cafasso

image.altText: Michelle Bullock and Philip Lowe

items.synopsis: RBA governor Philip Lowe says inflation is falling and the worst is over for interest rate increases, but rising property prices are complicating things.

title.children: RBA governor Philip Lowe says 'the worst is over' for interest rate rises, as his term nears its end

image.altText: James Redmond Burrows outside a court.

items.synopsis: Tasmanian tax agent James Redmond Burrows was entrusted with very large sums of money by his clients but "deliberately and systematically betrayed that trust over a lengthy period", a court has heard.

title.children: Tax accountant who stole nearly $1.5m from clients and tax office to fund gambling addiction jailed

image.altText: A waitress in a white shirt carries a tray of glasses in a Canberra restaurant.

title.children: 'Young people are hustlers': Gen Z 'willing to do what they need to' to make ends meet

image.altText: A man in a black shirt and cap crouches down next to a racing greyhound with a silk coat at a race track.

items.synopsis: Aerial footage taken at a Gary Johnson's greyhound facility is released by Animal Liberation Tasmania — with the trainer saying the presence of the drone had his animals "cowering like they've been interfered with".

title.children: 'There was nothing wrong': Greyhound trainer fires back at activist group over kennel drone footage

image.altText: A man sits on a rock

items.synopsis: A coroner has stopped parents of Luke Gilbert from giving their family impact statement after they refused to edit sections deemed "factually incorrect and offensive" by police.

title.children: Police shooting victim's swastika tattoos analysed as parents barred from making 'offensive' impact statement

image.altText: Japan's Riko Ueki puts her hands on her head as Sweden players celebrate behind her after a missed penalty.

items.synopsis: Sweden moves into the semifinals at the expense of 2011 Women's World Cup winners Japan, setting up a clash with Spain after La Roja beat Netherlands 2-1 in extra time. Follow live.

title.children: Sweden rescued twice by goalpost in thrilling Women's World Cup quarterfinal win over Japan

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Sweden hangs on! Incredible drama in Auckland! Sweden were so dominant for so long, but when Japan clicked, boy did they click! Japan missed a penalty! They had another shot dance its way across the line off just about every piece of woodwork and the keeper. They did not have a shot in the first hour but if they'd scored that penalty they might have ended up winning that game 7-2! However, it was Sweden who prevailed after their early dominance. It's heartbreak for the 2011 champions, but they are out - Sweden, the killers of previous World Cup winners, march on.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Full time: Japan 1-2 Sweden

children.content: (Getty Images)
Sweden hangs on!
Incredible drama in Auckland!
Sweden were so dominant for so long, but when Japan clicked, boy did they click!
Japan missed a penalty!
They had another shot dance its way across the line off just about every piece of woodwork and the keeper.
They did not have a shot in the first hour but if they'd scored that penalty they might have ended up winning that game 7-2!
However, it was Sweden who prevailed after their early dominance.
It's heartbreak for the 2011 champions, but they are out - Sweden, the killers of previous World Cup winners, march on.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's the substitute Honoka Hayashi with her first goal in international football! What a time to get it! Kiko Seike turned and twisted in the penalty area before crossing low, Sweden can't clear the ball and Hayashi scores! Game on?!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 88' GOAL JAPAN!

children.content: (Getty Images)
It's the substitute
Honoka Hayashi with her first goal in
international football!
What a time to get it!
Kiko Seike turned and twisted in the penalty area before crossing low, Sweden can't clear the ball and Hayashi scores!
Game on?!

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Oh my goodness! Riko Ueki slams the ball into the cross bar and the ball bounces down and away from danger. The referee had to check, but it did not cross the line by a fair distance - not like the milimetre that cost the USA in their shootout in the Round of 16. It was a terrifically struck penalty - but wayward. It's the sixth penalty miss of the tournament. That may well be that.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 76'  JAPAN MISS THE PENALTY!

children.content: Oh my goodness!
Riko Ueki slams the ball into the cross bar and the ball bounces down and away from danger.
(Getty Images)
The referee had to check, but it did not cross the line by a fair distance - not like the milimetre that cost the USA in their shootout in the Round of 16.
It was a terrifically struck penalty - but wayward.
It's the sixth penalty miss of the tournament.
That may well be that.
